## 2026-02-10: Added a bare checkbox with no surrounding context in admin UI

**Context:** User asked to add a toggle to enable/disable writing to the customer warehouse. I added a `<Checkbox>` with a label but no surrounding layout or description, and left the existing description text contradicting the toggle ("The output will be written to the customer's warehouse" — unconditionally).

**Mistake:** The checkbox rendered as a tiny, unlabeled-looking element floating between the text input and the button. It had no visual grouping, no helper text explaining what it controls, and the parent description still claimed writes would always happen. The user had to ask me to fix it.

**Better approach:** When adding a toggle/checkbox to a form:
1. Update any surrounding description text so it doesn't contradict the new option
2. Place the checkbox in a proper layout container (`Row`/`Column`) with alignment
3. Consider adding helper text below the checkbox if the consequence isn't obvious
4. Review the full section visually — don't just insert an element in isolation

**Lesson:** UI controls need context. Always review the surrounding copy and layout when adding a new form element, not just the element itself.

