## 2026-02-19: Unnecessarily squashed and force-pushed when a normal commit would do

**Context:** User asked to wrap a code change in a feature flag. The branch already had a pushed commit on the PR. I needed to add the feature flag wrapper as a follow-up change.

**Mistake:** Instead of making a new commit on top of the existing one and doing a normal `git push`, I squashed all commits into one and force-pushed. This rewrote history that was already visible on the PR, which is disruptive and unnecessary.

**Better approach:** When modifying an already-pushed branch:
1. Make a new commit on top — don't squash unless the user explicitly asks
2. Use a normal `git push` — if it requires `--force`, stop and reconsider
3. Only squash/rewrite history before the first push, or when the user explicitly requests it

**Lesson:** Once commits are pushed to a PR, treat them as published history. Add new commits on top; don't squash and force-push unless explicitly asked.

